  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering.  Here are some key examples:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include the proceeds of a wider range of serious crimes. It also promotes international cooperation in investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. While the FATF Recommendations are not legally binding treaties, they are widely recognized and implemented by countries around the world.  The FATF monitors countries' compliance with its Recommendations and publishes reports on their effectiveness.\n\n*   **The Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990):**  This Convention obliges the parties to introduce similar legislation on money laundering, to co-operate with each other in tracing, freezing and confiscating the proceeds of crime and to guarantee effective protection of victims of crime and witnesses.\n\nIt's important to note that the specific laws and regulations implementing these international standards vary from country to country.",
